title: For Sale:  Vertical Crossbow for Sale: 2012 Strother XS Rush 80 with Hickory Creek Draw-Loc BP
postcontent: Don't want to sell, but need money for bills, so this is a....This is a "Vertical Crossbow" in Excellent condition - I would even say pristine including the string, as follows:-2012 Strother XS Rush Bow with 80 lb limbs, shot very little (less than 70 shots, back in 2014; not since); includes D-loop, peep, and nice limb dampeners-Hickory Creek Draw-Loc Bullpup unit, with foot stirrup, anti-dry-fire device (which works very well), etc.-Hickory Creek Scope Mount unit for the Draw-Loc (pictured separately)-Trophy Taker Smack Down fall-away rest (so you can use feathers if you want; note that fall-aways that will work with Draw-Locs are hard to find and install, but this one works great)-Strother brand 5-pin aluminum camo sight, and basic rubber stabilizer (pictured separately). If you would like to sub out any of the following for the Strother-branded sight, I will do so at no charge:  "IQ" brand 4-pin sight, scope mount (picatinney) which mounts on the draw-loc arm for mounting a traditional scope, or a picatinney rail which goes on the riser in place of a regular front sight, which allows you to mount any red dot sight or similar that you want.So, ready to shoot. Note that I will install the sight and re-install the anti-dry-fire device for you if you want; your choice as to each one. If you put your fletching *WAY* back on the arrow, or use FOBs, you will want to just leave the anti-dry-fire device off - but it will still be shipped. Note that if you're not familiar with the large advantages of Hickory Creek Draw-Loc-based vertical crossbows over others, they:-Let you draw manually and very quickly, without any cocking device, and de-cock without having to shoot an arrow or have the weight and bulk of a crank mechanism. This allows you to hunt on the move, going quickly between your serial ambush spots / stands.  [Note that I know MT does not allow Xbows for hunting; I moved here from a state which does, 2 years ago].-Give you just about the same amount of velocity / energy as a much-higher draw weight traditional crossbow, due to greatly-increased powerstroke and efficiency. For example, this XS Rush has a 342 IBO with a very long powerstroke and efficient cams, so these 80 lb limbs really sling 'em. The 80% let off and H.C. trigger design allows a very nice trigger pull too.-Allow you to stalk hunt more easily and lean left or right up against a tree for stability for a shot, which horizontal limbs impede.Of course, if you're pretty stout, you can also use this Strother 80 as a regular manual bow.  It's got a 30" draw length in case you want to do that.I have over $1,100 into this rig. Your price is $810 FTF or $845 SHIPPED. Shipping is FedEx, insured (signature required vs. not required is up to you). If you live east of the Mississippi, and/or south of the Mason-Dixon, add $10 since FedEx is going to charge me more.Also please note that I have been buying, selling, and trading on the honor system for about 22 years without problems on various sites including ArcheryTalk, Thefiringline, Thehighroad, rimfirecentral, gunbroker, gunsamerica, ebay, Armslist, graybeardoutdoors, and several others.Thanks for looking. Text or call REDACTED to buy -  I can text more and better pics.IMPORTANT EDIT:  i just realized I made a huge mistake in taking the pictures and then also in my descriptions since I unthinkingly made the descriptions from the pictures. I put the wrong Draw-Loc arm on the wrong bow on my two listings here today, as follows. --The BULLPUP Draw-Loc arm, though pictured on this Strother rig, actually goes with the other one for sale - the Hickory Creek made rig.--Conversely, the REGULAR (non-bullpup) Draw-Loc arm, though pictured on the other one listed for sale in this forum., actually goes with this Strother rig.The draw lengths of each bow are specific to the arms, so they cannot be switched. This also makes sense as the other Hickory Creek inline rig is for holding in your hands, shooting free hand, stalking and such (well facilitated by the bullpup arm); whereas this Strother rig is larger and meant to be used (at least as far as how I used it) with a tripod supporting the rig via the stabilizer - the draw length is too long on that rig to comfortably reach the handle on the front riser anyway, so I shoot it with the bow suspended on a tripod, holding only the draw loc handle, with no hand at all on the bow riser. The prices listed are still correct, taking all into account. Sorry for all the confusion. I will add the new, corrected pictures later tonight as soon as I get a chance.

title: For Sale:  Chiappa M27E 9MM
postcontent: Model MC27 has a high quality, cold forged barrel with a right twist rate of 1:10 inches (1:250 mm) with six grooves. The barrel has a life expectancy of 40,000 bullets, a pretty significant amount for a critical part of the pistol. The slide is somewhat unusually shaped. has a somewhat unusual shape. It is reminiscent of the SIG-Sauer slides, but with a very narrow line, considering that its guide is on the inside of the frame. It is a no frills piece, slide has no additional elements, only the sights and finger grooves. Finger grooves make cocking of the gun much easier, which is a good thing, because the exposed slide surface is pretty narrow and could otherwise cause marksmen to lose their grip on it.
